{
  "answer": "**'The Wife's Lament'** (an anonymous Old English elegy, likely penned by a male monastic scribe) features a woman's raw first-person monologue of exile, betrayal, and unfulfilled vows after separation from her lord.[^1] Its most intimate line captures her endless isolation in a cave-dwelling: \"There I must sit the summer-long day, there I can weep for my paths of exile, my many sorrows; for I can never find any rest from my heart’s-care, nor from the longing that this life has brought me.\"[^2]\n\n**'Maa ka Khwab' ('Mother's Dream')** by Allama Iqbal (a 20th-century male philosopher-poet) is a dream-vision poem where a mother laments her son's departure, only for him to reveal her tears have extinguished his lamp of progress.[^3] Its most intimate line is the mother's direct plea: \"Your absence leaves me in deep turmoil; I string each day a garland of my tears.\"[^4]\n\nThe voice in **'Maa ka Khwab'** is more constructed and visibly mediated by the male author. It unfolds as a moral fable with a revelatory twist—the son's rebuke frames the mother's grief as counterproductive, aligning with Iqbal's themes of self-reliance and spiritual empowerment.[^5] This didactic structure (dream → vision → lesson) underscores the poet's imaginative ventriloquism for philosophical ends. By contrast, **'The Wife's Lament'** sustains an unbroken, anguished dramatic monologue without authorial intervention or moral resolution, evoking a more seemingly unmediated female intimacy amid its formulaic Old English style.[^6]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3 (*The Wife's Lament*), [full chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 (*Maa ka Khwab*), [full chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/).\n\n[^4]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-c4bed6).\n\n[^5]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc) (son's explanation).\n\n[^6]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 3, [full chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/).",
